ce:section.ce:para:
To address the abovementioned issues, we selected the diketopyrrolopyrrole (DPP) moiety to design novel chemosensors for Cr (VI) detection (source from HCrO4
                     −). The most significant reason is that, compared with most of other building blocks, DPP has two flanking groups which can be facilely modified to provide multiple possibilities to turn the optical properties and capacities to interact with analytes for reliable sensing performance [39,40]. Moreover, DPP itself has other merits for sensing applications. For example, it is a stable and colorful dye molecule, enabling colorimetric sensing in harsh conditions for visible detection. It is a commercially available low-cost material, supporting large-scale sensing applications. It is a strong electron-deficient unit to form strong electronic coupling and efficient intramolecular charge transfer along the whole molecule for enhanced signal amplification and lowered LOD. With these merits, DPP-derived materials have been applied for various target analytes sensing. Utilizing the reaction of toxic CN− with CO bond, Jeong et al. developed a colorimetric and fluorescent sensor (Sens 1 in Fig. 1
                     ) with LOD of 1–10 μM in CH2Cl2 [41]. Furthermore, Gholami et al. replaced benzene with fluorescent naphthalene to enhance the fluorescence property (Sens 5) and therefore significantly lowered the LOD to 0.04 μM in aqueous media [42]. Another reactive site in DPP for promising sensing applications is the unsubstituted amide group. As presented in Fig. 1, with a mono-substituted hydrophilic glycol chain, Sens 2 behaves promising Hg2+ detection with a super low LOD of 0.011 μM in water [43]. Qu et al. reported the charge transfer process from DPP to triphenylamine or vice versa before and after reacting with F− from the unsubstituted amide group (Sens 6), which enables a red fluorescence quenching for selective F− sensing [44]. Flanking groups have multiple options to react with various anions/cations for sensing applications. For example, the pyridinium salt can be recovered to aromatic pyridine with ONOO− (Sens 3), being a reliable method for ONOO− sensing [45]. With boronic acid ester group to react with F−, furan flanked DPP (Sens 4) acts as a smart sensor for quantitative detection of F− [46]. Zhang et al. reported that the photoinduced electron transfer (PET) process from nitrogen-rich end group to DPP can be blocked by Zn2+ owing to the binding with lone pair electrons of nitrogen atoms (Sens 7), making it a fluorescent off-on sensor selectively for Zn2+ [47]. Even by reacting with different cations from specific reactive sites, Kaur et al. reported that Sens 9 can act as Hg2+ and Cu2+ sensor with naked eye detection [48]. Except for small molecules, copolymerizing DPP with specific monomer is another promising method to develop sensors. An typical example is to utilize the addition of Br2 to Te atom for Br2 detection (Sens 8) as reported by Kaur et al., which enables not only visible color changes in solution and film but also significant and reversible current variations in OFETs [49].
